          "Models",
          "Assessment Strategy",
          "Performance Metric: Best Model",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "E-Learning",
          "Abandoning a Course",
          "Dropout (1) vs No Dropout (0)",
          "60000 university students",
          "920 courses at Université of Montreal",
          "LMS logs",
          "[Flag Evaluations, Speed Coefficient, Consultation Coefficient, Count Events]",
          "Week 12 of 15",
          "The authors consider 2 distinct datasets → one for student behaviour containing the Student logs and a second for clustering that contains information about the different courses.\n\nCourses are clustered by different characteristics of behavior…\n\nEach cluster will have its own classifier of dropout. This approach makes sense because different courses have very different ways of working.\n\nLog events were aggreagated into different constructs and were subsequently scaled using RobustScaler. ",
          "Logistic Regression, Random Forest, GBoost, xGBoost, AdaBoost",
          "10-Fold Cross-Validation",
          "{Precision: 0.567 - 25 clusters, Recall: 0.289 - 5 clusters, F1-Score: 0.416 - 5 Clusters, Accuracy: 0.95 - 12 Clusters, AUC: 0.642 - 5 clusters, Log-Loss: 0.653 - 12 clusters}",
          "In total, the authors obtained 25 clusters, 12 clusters and 5 clusters and for each cluster there were 5 candidate algorithms → 210 models being trained. \n\nIn total, the authors created and deployed 42 models → one per cluster.\n\nMetrics show that performances do not vary significantly regardless of the number of clusters considered, but 5 clusters is the winner on most metrics. ",
          "No hyper-paramenter tuning is done.\n\nVery specific online context (Covid-Era)\n\nDoes not consider all resources available. \n\nDoes not consider information outside of Moodle.\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 4
    }
  ],
